flowRoot.flowPara: > Open software (open source) are ubiquitous. Most of the applications we use every day are not open software, but they are all produced using open software.
> The foundations of the digital are based on open software, which is shaping the development of new technologies: the web, cloud data centres, cryptocurrencies, AI, etc.
> Complex ecosystems of players are being structured around open software responding to common needs, leading to new challenges in producing and maintaining these resources.
Software whose source code can be freely used, modified and shared, enabling a whole range of open and decentralised collaborative practices.

A digital common is a resource used and produced by a community with relatively shared governance. It can be software, educational or scientific content, hardware, data, etc. with an ecosystem made up of citizens, private organisations and/or public institutions.
In the case of the Linux kernel, between 2007 and 2019, 1,730 organisations have contributed to the software.
Python, JavaScript, PHP, C, C++... In computing, these different "languages" are used to write software code.

For each language there is software to convert this text, which can be understood by humans, into instructions for the computer, which only understands 0s and 1s. The software to run these languages is mostly open source which makes it easy for anyone to do programming.

A kernel is the software that is essential to the operation of a computer. It is the interface that enables communication between all the software and hardware components of the computer (memory, keyboard, mouse, screen, camera, etc.). Linux is the kernel that powers the majority of mobile phones (Android is based on Linux), websites, connected objects, etc. 100% of the 500 largest supercomputers use Linux. Today, Linux is the most important open software and can be found everywhere with the digital.

flowRoot.flowPara: A forge is an environment that offers a range of features for the collaborative development of a resource. You can find in the same place a versioning and history management tool, a bug-tracking system, forum-type discussion areas, a wiki, and so on. There are mainly software forges, but the principle can be applied to other forms of content.
GitHub and GitLab are the 2 most popular forges.
